Abstract

This analysis uses linear and robust regression models to predict healthcare charges based on patient factors. The robust model is preferable due to its resistance to outliers. Key drivers of higher costs are smoking, high BMI, more children, and Northeast region. To reduce spending, the report recommends focusing on smoking cessation, healthy BMI, family planning, and analyzing regional cost differences. Targeting modifiable health risks through public health initiatives could significantly curb rising healthcare expenditures.

Introduction

Medical costs billed by health insurance are a major concern for individuals and policymakers alike. Understanding the factors that contribute to these costs is essential for developing effective strategies to control them.

The dataframe used in this report contains information on the following variables:

  • Age
  • Sex
  • BMI
  • Children
  • Smoker
  • Region
  • Charges

The objective of this report is to understand drivers of healthcare costs and provide recommendations to reduce spending.

Removing Duplicate Rows

remove_duplicates <- function(df) {
  # Find duplicated rows
  dup_rows <- duplicated(df) | duplicated(df, fromLast = TRUE)
  
  # If there are no duplicated rows, return the original data frame
  if (!any(dup_rows)) {
    cat("No duplicates found\n")
    return(df)
  }
  
  # Find the row indices of the duplicated rows
  dup_indices <- which(dup_rows)
  
  # Group the duplicated rows by their values
  groups <- split(dup_indices, apply(df[dup_rows, ], 1, paste, collapse = ""))
  
  # Print a message to inform the user that duplicate rows were found
  cat("Duplicate rows found at indices:\n")
  
  # For each group of duplicated rows
  for (group in groups) {
    # Sort the row indices in ascending order
    group <- sort(group)
    
    # Print the row indices of the duplicates
    cat(paste(group, collapse = ", "), "\n")
    
    # Keep the row with the lowest index and remove the rest
    df <- df[!duplicated(df), ]
  }
  
  return(df)
}
df <- remove_duplicates(df)
## Duplicate rows found at indices:
## 1, 4, 14, 18 
## 112, 455 
## 201, 588 
## 555, 722, 898, 1233 
## 22, 66, 88


The remove_duplicates function identifies and removes duplicate rows from a data frame. It first checks for any duplicated rows in the input data frame. If duplicates exist, it groups these duplicates and prints their indices. The function then retains only the first occurrence from each group of duplicates and removes the rest.

In this case, duplicates were found at indices 1, 4, 14, 18; 112, 455; 201, 588; 555, 722, 898, 1233; and 22, 66, 88. The function successfully eliminated these duplicates, returning a data frame df containing only unique rows.

MCAR checking

# Set the significance level
alpha <- 0.05

# Perform Little's MCAR test

mcar_test_result <- function(df) {
  # Perform Little's MCAR test
  mcar_result <- mcar_test(df)
  
  print(mcar_result)
  
  cat("\n")
  
  cat("# Null hypothesis: The data are missing completely at random (MCAR).\n")
  
  cat("# Alternative hypothesis: Among a set of variables, at least one of them has missing values that are not missing completely at random.\n")
  
  cat("\n")
  
  # Decide whether to reject or not reject the null hypothesis
  if (mcar_result$p.value < alpha) {
    cat("Reject the null hypothesis: Among a set of variables, at least one of them has missing values that are not missing completely at random.\n\n")
  } else {
    cat("Do not reject the null hypothesis: The data are missing completely at random (MCAR).\n\n")
  }
}
mcar_test_result(df)

Model Selection and Evaluation

Splitting Data into Training and Test Sets

split_data <- function(data, size) {
  # Set the seed for random number generation
  set.seed(123)
  
  # Get the number of rows in the data
  n <- nrow(data)
  
  # Generate a random sample of row indices for the training data
  id <- sample(1:n, size = size * n)
  
  # Create the training data by selecting the rows with the sampled indices
  train_data <- data[id, ]
  
  # Create the test data by selecting the rows not in the training data
  test_data <- data[-id, ]
  
  # Return a list containing the training and test data
  list(train = train_data, test = test_data)
}
splitData <- split_data(df_clean, 0.8)
train_data <- splitData$train
test_data <- splitData$test


The df_log dataframe is partitioned into training and testing datasets using an 80/20 split. This means that 80% of the data is randomly allocated to the training dataset, while the remaining 20% is assigned to the testing dataset.

Automated Model Selection and Multimodel Inference with (G)LMs

h_model <- glmulti(charges ~ .,
        data   = train_data,
        method = "h",       # Exhaustive approach
        crit   = aicc,      # AICC corrected AIC for small samples
        level  = 1,         # 2 with interactions, 1 without
        family = gaussian,
        plotty = FALSE,
        report = FALSE,
        fitfunction = glm,  # Type of model (LM, GLM, GLMER etc.)
        confsetsize = 100,)  # Keep 100 best models
print(h_model)

Training Linear Regression Model

set.seed(42)

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv",
                     number = 10,
                     repeats = 10,
                     verboseIter = FALSE)

lm_model <- train(charges ~ .,
                  data = train_data,
                  method = "lm",
                  metric = "RMSE",
                  preProcess = c("scale", "center"),
                  trControl = ctrl)


The code executes a linear regression model fitting on the train_data dataset. Initially, a random seed is established at 42 to ensure reproducibility. Subsequently, a cross-validation control object is configured with 10 folds and repeated 10 times, opting for non-verbose iteration. In the final step, the lm method from the caret package is employed to train a linear regression model. The model utilizes the train_data dataset to predict charges based on all other variables in the dataset. The Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) serves as the metric for evaluating the performance of the model. The data is preprocessed by scaling and centering before training.

Converting Log-Scaled Coefficients to Original Scale

coefToScale <- function(model, coefs) {

  # Initialize final_coefs
  final_coefs <- numeric(length(coefs))

  # Apply (exp(coefs) - 1) only for the intercept
  final_coefs[1] <- exp(coefs[1]) - 1

  # Apply (exp(coefs) - 1) * 100 for the rest
  final_coefs[-1] <- (exp(coefs[-1]) - 1) * 100

  # Assign names to the final_coefs vector
  names(final_coefs) <- names(coefs)

  return(final_coefs)
}

  • smokeryes: Being a smoker (as compared to the reference group, non-smokers) is associated with having approximately 87.67% higher charges, on average.
  • regionnorthwest: Being in the northwest region (as compared to the reference group, northeast region) is associated with having approximately 2.65% lower charges, on average. However, this result is not statistically significant at an alpha level of 0.05.
  • regionsoutheast: Being in the southeast region (as compared to the reference group, northeast region) is associated with having approximately 8.42% lower charges, on average.
  • regionsouthwest: Being in the southwest region (as compared to the reference group, northeast region) is associated with having approximately 5.83% lower charges, on average.

Creating a Dataframe to Compare RMSE of Linear and Ridge & Lasso Regression Models

# Create a vector for each model
lm <- c(RMSE_train = rmse_lm_train, RMSE_test = rmse_lm_test)
rlm <- c(RMSE_train = rmse_rlm_train, RMSE_test = rmse_rlm_test)

# Combine the vectors into a dataframe
rmse_df <- rbind(lm, rlm)

# Name the rows
rownames(rmse_df) <- c("Linear Regression", "Robust Regression")

# Print the dataframe
print(rmse_df)
##                   RMSE_train RMSE_test
## Linear Regression  0.4552644 0.4162629
## Robust Regression  0.4701139 0.4170331


The analysis reveals comparable performance between the linear model (lm) and the robust linear model in terms of Root Mean Square Error (RMSE).

The RMSE values for both models are close. The lm model exhibits a RMSE of approximately 0.455 on the training data and 0.416 on the test data. The robust linear model shows a slightly higher RMSE of approximately 0.470 on the training data and 0.417 on the test data. This suggests similar levels of accuracy in predictions from both models, with no consistent outperformance by either model.

Moreover, a high correlation (approximately 0.935) exists between the two models, indicating highly correlated but not identical predictions.

In conclusion, both models demonstrate comparable performance in this analysis. The choice between them depends on other considerations such as interpretability or computational efficiency.

Given the slightly lower RMSE of the Linear Regression model on both training and test datasets, it appears to be slightly more accurate in its predictions.

However, considering the presence of outliers and violations of the assumptions of multiple linear regression in the data, the robust linear model (rlm) emerges as a better choice for this data. The rlm model is designed to be more resistant to outliers and violations of assumptions than the standard linear model (lm). Despite a slightly higher RMSE in this analysis, the rlm models resistance to outliers potentially makes it more reliable and accurate when predicting new data that may also contain outliers.

This is because it is designed to be more resistant to such issues.

Conclusion and Recommendation

The analysis shows that the linear regression model and robust linear regression model have comparable performance in predicting healthcare charges, with close Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) values. However, the robust model is likely preferable given the presence of outliers and violations of assumptions in the data. Its resistance to outliers can make it more reliable for future unseen data.

The lower RMSE for test data suggests the model is slightly more accurate in predicting new data versus training data. But high overall RMSE indicates room for improvement in predictive accuracy.

Considering factors like interpretability, computational efficiency, and resistance to outliers, the robust linear regression model is recommended over the standard linear model. Despite a slightly higher RMSE, it is more resistant to issues like outliers that violate assumptions.

To reduce healthcare costs based on model coefficients, it is recommended to:

  • Focusing on reducing smoking rates, as smoking has a very strong association with higher charges. Smoking cessation programs could provide significant savings.

  • Encouraging maintenance of healthy BMI levels, as increased BMI is tied to higher costs. Lifestyle or dietary changes helping patients achieve a healthy BMI may help control rising expenses.

  • Improving access to family planning resources, as having more children is linked to increased costs. Enabling better family planning could potentially reduce expenditures.

  • Analyzing regional differences, specifically higher average costs in the Northeast, to uncover opportunities to reduce spending.

Overall, targeting modifiable health risks like smoking and obesity through public health efforts to promote healthy lifestyles could help curb rising healthcare costs.
